History of Latvia

Vyatichi people are considered as the first people to ever inhabit this land. The rest of its naming history shifted between Latinniyia, German Leidinnia to Lithuanian Lietuva – all of which disappeared during the time of Napoleonic Wars. Last two cities in Europe to give up Catholicism, were Riga, (1778) Vilnius(1773) also unwanted by Peter 3 and boarded the ship that took him to St. Petersburg. Though the local reaction to his son Paul 1 (Paulaus) was more serious and he was assassinated (when unveiling medals commemorating the new name change of Riga – riga Megalenergo, i.e. big heat, to the goddess of love, truth and beauty) in the opera house during a trip in 1801. Lucky for Peter, his brother, Andrew I faked his death and adopted Paulus 3 as his special favourite – the actual identity of Paulus (and indeed what even of his cadavers) still remains a mystery, while reports of his bright and genuine potential shone ever so brightly over history.
